Interview Questions
1) How do you declare an array in Java? What are the three ways to declare an array?
-->👉 Definition: An array is a collection of similar data types stored in contiguous memory locations.

✅ Ways to declare:
int[] arr;     // preferred
int arr[];     
int []arr;     


2) How do you instantiate an array?
-->👉 Using new keyword:
int[] arr = new int[5];


3) Can you declare and instantiate an array in a single line?
-->✅ Yes:

    int[] arr = new int[5];
    
    Or directly initialize:
    
    int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};



4) Can an array have zero size?
-->✅ Yes:

int[] arr = new int[0];

👉 Valid but cannot store elements




5) Can you declare an array without specifying size? and is it valid to instantiate an array with a negative
size in Java?
-->❓ Without size:
    
    ❌ Not allowed unless initialized
    
    int[] arr = new int[]; // ❌ ERROR
    ❓ Negative size:
    
    ❌ Runtime error:
    
    int[] arr = new int[-5]; // ❌ NegativeArraySizeException



6) How is an array object stored in memory?
-->Array object → stored in Heap
    Reference variable → stored in Stack
    
    High-Level Memory SplitStack Memory:
    Stores the reference variable (the "pointer" to the array). If you declare int[] arr, the identifier arr lives here.
    Heap Memory: Stores the actual array object and all its elements. This memory is managed by the Java Garbage Collector.



7) What is the difference between stack and heap in context of arrays?
-->
| Stack            | Heap                |
| ---------------- | ------------------- |
| Stores reference | Stores actual array |
| Fast access      | Larger memory       |
| Method-based     | Object-based        |



8) Can array size be changed after instantiation?
-->❌ No
👉 Arrays are fixed size
✔️ Alternative: Use ArrayList



9) Difference between new int[5] and int[]arr= {1,2,3,4,5}
-->new int[5]
    int[] arr = new int[5];
    Size = 5
    Default values = 0
    {1,2,3,4,5}
    int[] arr = {1,2,3,4,5};
